english:
  title: Stele Inscription for the New Confucian Temple and School of the Joseon Kingdom Under the Ming
  author: Byeon Gyeyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the seventh year of Yongle, in the autumn of the jiaxu year, in the ninth month, the King commanded me, his subject Gyeyeong, saying: "Our late father, the Taejo, received Heaven's luminous mandate and established our realm, fixing the capital at Hanyang. He urgently built the Confucian temple and academy to honor the sage and elevate teaching. I, inheriting this great legacy and following the established laws, have ordered the renovation of the temple. It is now complete. The school officials, including Choe Ham, have requested that these words be inscribed in stone for future generations. You must write this."

    Your subject Gyeyeong, receiving this command with reverence, withdrew to investigate the origins of this undertaking.

    In the jiashu year, when Taejo established the capital, the rites governing shrine, altar, court, market, walls, and palaces all found their proper expression. He immediately planned the construction of the temple and academy, selecting a site in the northeastern corner of the capital. The mountains rose majestically, the earth was fertile, waters flowed in circling channels, and the position faced south. He entrusted Lord Min Je of Yeohung with the work. Artisans were gathered, materials prepared, and construction began in the third month of the jingchou year, completing in the seventh month of the wuyin year.

    The Sage and the Ten Worthies were enshrined in the lofty hall, while those receiving secondary offerings were arranged in the side chambers. The academy stood behind the temple, with the Hall of Illuminating Virtue in the center. Side chambers stood to left and right, with connecting galleries extending southward. To the east of the left chamber were administrative rooms and corridors, with stations for teachers and students, administrative offices—nothing left incomplete. The structures were grand and spacious, their construction solid and enduring. All buildings, great and small, numbered ninety-six bays. Fields were established to provide sacrificial offerings and stipends for students, while census households were exempted to serve in cleaning and labor.

    The temple and academy seemed complete. Yet fire consumed them in the second month of the gengchen year.

    That same year, in the eleventh month, the King ascended the throne at Songgyeong. He proceeded to the academy to pay respects to the Sage, commanding the crown prince to study there. In the yiyou year, upon returning to the capital, he personally made offerings to both Sage and Teacher. Three years later, in the first month of the dinghai year, he ordered the temple reconstructed on its original site. Lord Yi Jik of Sungsan and Official Park Ja-cheong oversaw the work with unwavering dedication—from dawn to dusk they inspected, devised plans, and directed labor. Within four months, the temple was completed, surpassing the old structure in loftiness, depth, elegance, and grandeur.

    A divine kitchen was built to the west of the temple, with eastern and western gates below the pavilions. Additional fields and servants were granted, the fields extending to ten thousand acres or more, the servants numbering three hundred.

    Following the proposal of Left Prime Minister Ha Ryun, the Sage Zengzi and Yan Hui were elevated to positions of co-worship, and Zixhang to the rank of Ten Worthies. Thus the temple's arrangements became beyond reproach.

    Your subject reflects: the Way of the Sage is vast and defies complete praise. Though one might speak of it, one would scarcely avoid the error of attempting to paint Heaven and Earth or draw the sun and moon.

    Our Master was born in the twilight of Zhou, gathering into himself the great accomplishment of all sages, establishing the great model for all future kings and transmitting teachings eternal. His influence touched the very beginning of transformation; his grace flows without end. Since humanity first arose, none has equaled his magnitude. When Zaiyu said the Master surpassed even Yao and Shun, he spoke with cause.

    Since Tang times, everywhere under heaven his temples stand in sight of one another, honored worship without error. How much more our Eastern Land, where since ancient days the customs have honored propriety, where people revere the Eight Precepts of Jizi, where human relationships are properly ordered, where institutions and culture rival those of China itself—where indeed the Master once wished to dwell.

    Thus our establishment of temple and academy, our elevation of teaching, can in no way be compared to other lands.

    We humbly consider: Taejo the Kangbyeon-daewang, responding to Heaven's mandate and following the people's will, founded this great enterprise and came to possess our realm. Upon establishing the capital, he made it his first priority to honor the sages and promote the Way of Confucius—his reverence for virtue and love of the Way flowing from his very nature, his vision for governance's true source and urgent necessity unmatched. Thus he left provision for his descendants' flourishing, purified the hearts of his people, and secured the nation's lifeblood. How profound!

    Our present King embodies benevolence, filial piety, humility, and reverence; he possesses strength, rectitude, clarity, and wisdom. He gloriously continues his predecessor's work, and in moments of leisure from governance, delights in studying the Classics and Histories, often reading late into the night, perfecting the investigation of things and extension of knowledge, exhaustively cultivating sincerity and rectification of heart. Searching the annals of antiquity, such rulers are scarcely to be found.

    Now the age flourishes and culture spreads. Merit families, great ministers, all officials and departments, even the palace guard—none are without scholarly aspiration. Is this not the fruit of our Taejo's honoring of learning and cultivation of talent, and our King's magnification of the ancestral legacy, his own practice serving to inspire the multitude and transform the people?

    With an academy where study is perfected and a temple where offerings are made, as one moves through the spaces—ascending and descending with reverence, observing and reflecting—virtue is completed and talent fulfilled. Those who serve the ruler and benefit the people emerge in succession. Thus may we anticipate that age of sage-kings when talent bloomed as in the Three Dynasties—not merely changing appearances for a moment's brilliance, but securing eternal blessing for our nation's shrine and state.

    Your subject Gyeyeong humbly bows and offers this inscription:

    Oh, the Venerable Sage, responding to the age in which he was born,
    Gathering the great wisdom from Fuxi through the Zhou,
    Since mankind first arose,
    Who has achieved such magnificence?

    Shining bright, his temples of honor
    Spread across all lands beneath heaven.
    How much more in the realm of Jizi,
    Where propriety has been held supreme,
    Where reverent bows and sacrificial rites
    Have been the ancient way.

    Heaven blessed our Taejo,
    Possessing both sacred and martial virtue,
    Bright receiver of Heaven's mandate,
    Accomplisher of great deeds.

    Setting his sacred capital
    Upon Hanyang's slopes,
    He established the academy,
    With the Sage's temple at its heart.

    Through ritual and instruction,
    The scholars gathered like shadows.
    Our brilliant King,
    Inheriting and expanding his father's work,
    Continues the illumination of sage learning,
    Rare in all ages.

    In the splendid new temple,
    Zengzi and Yan Hui are elevated,
    The heir enters the academy,
    And the nation's foundation grows strong.

    Our founder built, our king perfected,
    Honoring the Sage,
    Nurturing countless talents,
    Until transformation itself became beautiful.

    Who lacks inborn nature?
    Yet men abandon and lose their own.
    If daily learning advances,
    And the world daily moves toward order,
    We may then hope to surpass even the five sages,
    And set a date for its coming.

    Hua Mountain stands lofty and grand,
    The Han waters flow on endlessly,
    With the nation's span infinite,
    Bear witness to the Sage's eternal worship.
    Inscribed upon stone for endless ages,
    These words shall remain.
  footnotes:
